Modular Chains

Celestia The Fault in Our Stars

Andrew Dyer
Seth Bloomberg
Kinji Steimetz

Sep 20, 2024   8 min read

Primer

Celestia has not had a great 2024. The native token, TIA, is down a whopping 55% YTD, while other major assets like BTC and SOL are comfortably up by 25-40%. While a part of the underperformance may be explained by period bias TIA had a significant run-up in Nov-Dec 2023 more importantly, its data availability (DA) narrative has suffered.

The consensus view on data availability has become that it is commoditized and, as such, will never receive a premium. Additionally, competition has heated up with multiple major launches, including EigenDA and Avail. Even Ethereum, with its large network effects, multiple major rollups, and limited throughput, has not been making much money from DA, so what hope do other DA layers have?

Thats the narrative, at least. On fundamentals, Celestia has grown its DA business. Since the launch of Eclipses mainnet, the amount of data posted to Celestia has grown significantly. Celestia now rivals Ethereum on the amount of data posted. However, this has not translated to higher fees Celestia's daily fees still average less than $1,000.

Going forward, there are two opposing forces acting on Celestias narrative

Improving Fundamentals

  • Its rollup ecosystem is slowly growing and becoming real. Seriously. Movement, Initia, SpiceNet, Astria EVM, Forma, and other novel rollups are expected to come online soon; beyond the rollups that are already live, like Dymension, Saga, Mantle, and Eclipse.
  • Its first mainnet upgrade, Lemongrass, recently went live, improving its pricing model and future upgradability, among other things. Celestia also announced its roadmap to scale its DA towards 1 GiB blocks with latency and scale similar to Web-2.
  • Finally, real improvements are coming from the intersection of ZK and decentralized DA. Prism provides an authentication standard for private messaging in an attempt to turn the Web from Dont Be Evil to Cant Be Evil.

Supply Unlocks

On the other hand, Celestia has a massive cliff unlock coming up at the end of October. The Celestia supply and liquid market cap will almost double overnight. Our analysis of historical unlocks found evidence of underperformance in tokens undergoing large unlocks. However, the effect isnt pervasive, we also found instances when product launches and vesting schedule changes can overcome this effect.

The outlook on Celestia boils down to the following questions

  • Is data availability a useful service that can sustainably charge a premium?
  • Do Celestias improving fundamentals outweigh the still low fees?
  • Does TIA have demand catalysts that can overcome the potentially massive sell pressure from upcoming unlocks?

Andrew

From a market positioning perspective, it can be helpful to look at historical examples as we did in our unlocks piece. DYDXs large rallies around its unlock caught many off-guard, both on the initial delay and when the event actually occurred. But based on funding rates and open interest at the time, fewer traders and investors seemed to have been positioned aggressively short into those events. Open interest was muted and funding rates were modestly positive. A recent and perhaps more applicable situation might be the AEVO unlock on May 15 of this year. AEVOs circulating supply jumped from around 122 million to 950 million tokens in a single event. While the relative increase in supply is much greater than TIAs, sentiment around AEVO being very overvalued for a perp DEX was similar to TIAs sentiment today.

The event ultimately put in a short-term bottom for AEVO as price bounced almost 50% in the following weeks. TIAs funding has reached more than -200% annualized and based on a ramp in open interest, shorts may be doubling down amid a 50% squeeze off local lows. There is certainly a lot of room for this positioning to unwind and propel TIA higher in the short-term, and possibly even a few weeks post-event like AEVO. However, whether TIA follows AEVOs steady down-trend afterwards will largely depend on it successfully growing into its valuation.

Seth

Celestia provides consensus and DA over its blockspace, priced and denominated in its native asset (TIA). So, even though it's bucketed as a DA Layer, in essence, it provides the same service as most other blockchains creating, selling, and securing blockspace.

Of course, unlike many other blockchains, Celestia doesnt have a native virtual machine (VM) or execution environment. Rollups must then bring their own execution environment and leverage the blockspace, along with consensus and DA, provided by Celestia.

If one zooms out, this closely mirrors Ethereum's rollup-centric vision. So, to answer the first question, just as Ethereum is in the process of discovering, the margins on pure DA services are thin and are only likely to compress further due to robust competitive forces.

To answer the second question, for Celestia (and, likely, Ethereum) to be successful, we need to live in a world with thousands or millions of rollups. We may be marching towards that world more slowly than some enjoy or had imagined, but the growth in the number of rollups deploying on Celestia is a positive sign that we are progressing towards that world nonetheless. In the short-to-medium term, even as the number of rollups building on Celestia grows, accrued fees will remain low and effectively negligible. The bet on Celestia here is that the positive growth trend continues, with Celestia and TIA finding value in other areas.

The previous sentence also partially answers the third and final question. Realistically, no one knows the short-term price action for TIA or virtually any other crypto asset. However, $1 billion of supply opening up within a relatively nascent market requires monumental conviction to balance out. The bull case here is found by understanding Celestia on a relative basis. If one believes that Celestia and Ethereum (and maybe Solana?) are all converging on the same path, then its not unreasonable to assume a similar growth trajectory for Celestia regarding both the network and the native asset. And if that turns out to be the case, short-term volatility (whether to the upside or downside) around supply unlocks ultimately is a non-factor.

Kinji

As discussed, the common belief is that large token unlocks create sell pressure, leading to negative price action in the days or weeks following the event. This sentiment is evident in TIA's perpetual markets, where there is significant short interest as traders anticipate future sell-offs.

A contrarian view is that Celestias fundamentals have improved to the point where token holders may not rush to exit their positions once the tokens unlock. In other words, some argue that the market is overestimating the selling pressure tied to the unlock. While this could be true, the longer-term outlook for TIA still hinges on investor demand. In the short term, demand might come from short positions being squeezed, but sustained growth will require sidelined capital to enter TIA positions. While TIA proponents believe capital is on the sidelines due to upcoming unlocks, I think the real reason is that TIA is still expensive.

Despite its improving fundamentals, TIA still needs to justify its valuation. With Celestia generating $1,000 in daily fees, its $6.5B FDV translates to over a 17,000x FDV-to-annualized fees multiple. Assuming this multiple normalizes to 50x, the current valuation implies a 35,000% growth in fees. While some may back this thesis, its unlikely the market will find this risk-reward appealing, and sidelined capital may explore other opportunities before considering TIA.

Kunal

While integrated blockchains have outperformed in H1 2024, the modularity thesis is winning the second half. Solana, a champion of the integrated thesis, will soon have a case of Layer-2s or network extensions as it calls them. On Ethereum, Layer-2s that vastly exceed alt-L1 throughput are coming up, including the much-awaited and hyped MegaETH. Modularity, it seems, is inevitable.

There is a simple logic for this. Among the key principles of blockchain design is the idea that proof verification is cheaper than execution. So, even if a blockchain has a highly scalable design, it would still be cheaper to run transactions on Layer-2 while leaving the base layer for validation and verification.

Another reason for this is that Layer-1s will always be limited by network overhead and consensus, whereas Layer-2s can eliminate them to maximize performance, truly limited only by hardware if it runs on a single sequencer like MegaETH.

In this universe, where Layer-2s are objectively better at execution, the base layers are useful for their network effects, decentralization, security, and data availability. Celestia is the first blockchain built solely for the purpose of providing DA to a network of rollups and is among the few that have Data Availability Sampling (DAS) live. As such, it is well-positioned to compete with other DA layers.

However, this is a medium-term thesis that will play out over a year or longer. It also requires the launch of exciting new applications on big and many rollups that will use the abundant DA. For the immediate term, I refer readers to Andrews report, which uses a data-driven approach to explain the effects of cliff unlocks.
